* NBC News cuts: CNN was not the only news network to reduce headcount this=
 week. NBC News also laid off more than 40 of its employees, mostly in prod=
uction=E2=80=94the latest news organization
to shed costs as companies resize their ambitions and audiences tune out fo=
r the Trump era. Of course, most of these cost savings are pretty minor, wi=
th networks like NBC preferring the long slow bleed of incremental layoffs =
rather than the one-fell-swoop mass firings that redefined the tech industr=
y during the =E2=80=9922 correction. Alas, nobody at 30 Rock will be breath=
ing a sigh of relief if they dodged this week=E2=80=99s bullet.
* Letter to the editor: Famed and
curmudgeonly Times columnist Paul Krugman has shed some light on his recent=
 surprise departure from the paper, blaming an =E2=80=9Cextremely intrusive=
=E2=80=9D editing process that apparently toned down the professor=E2=80=99=
s voice. =E2=80=9CI approached Mondays and Thursdays with dread, and often =
spent the afternoon in a rage,=E2=80=9D Krugman told Columbia Journalism Re=
view this week. He said his editor, Patrick Healy, =E2=80=9Coften=E2=80=94n=
ot always=E2=80=94rewrote crucial passages; I would then do a
rewrite of his rewrite to restore the original sense, and felt that I was p=
utting more work=E2=80=94certainly more emotional energy=E2=80=94into repai=
ring the damage from his editing than I put into writing the original draft=
=2E It=E2=80=99s true that nothing was pub=
lished without my approval; but the=
 back-and-forth, to my eye, both made my life hell and left the columns fla=
t and colorless.=E2=80=9D

Krugman wouldn=E2=80=99t be the first or last writer to complain about his =
editor, of course. But it=E2=80=99s worth noting that the
Princeton economist was never quite known for any sort of inimitable or Tol=
stoyan style, though the Times afforded him a tremendous amount of latitude=
=2E After all, the man who was hired af=
ter his groundbreaking, Nobel-winning=20=
work on economies of scale eventually morphed into another member of the #R=
esistance choir that became the Times op-ed page. Meanwhile, the Opinion se=
ction seems to be receiving a long-overdue tune-up. Charles Blow and Pamela
Paul, long standbys, are leaving the paper, too.

And now, CNN=E2=80=A6

CNN After CNN

